{"title_page": "Africans in Guangzhou", "text_new": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group= Africans in Guangzhou\n|population= 10,344 (2017)<ref name=\"pop2017\">{{cite news|title=Guangzhou community shrinks under police pressure, economic changes|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1039623.shtml|agency=[[Global Times]]|date=March 26, 2017}}</ref>\n|popplace= \n|langs= [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], [[Igbo language|Igbo]], [[Bambara language|Bambara]] and other [[Languages of Africa|African languages]]\n|rels= {{hlist| [[Christianity]] | [[Islam]] | [[Traditional African religion|traditional faiths]] }}\n|related= \n}}{{Chinese\n|order=st\n|s=\u5e7f\u5dde\u975e\u88d4\n|t=\u5ee3\u5dde\u975e\u88d4\n|p=Gu\u01cengzh\u014du F\u0113iy\u00ec\n|j=gwong2 zau1 fei1 jeoi6\n|l=Guangzhou residents of African descent\n|s2=\u5e7f\u5dde\u9ed1\u4eba\n|t2=\u5ee3\u5dde\u9ed1\u4eba\n|p2=Gu\u01cengzh\u014du h\u0113ir\u00e9n\n|j2=gwong2 zau1 hak1 jan4\n|l2=Black people in Guangzhou\n}}\n'''Africans in Guangzhou''' ({{zh|s=\u5e7f\u5dde\u975e\u88d4|t=\u5ee3\u5dde\u975e\u88d4}}, more commonly {{zh|s=\u5e7f\u5dde\u9ed1\u4eba|t=\u5ee3\u5dde\u9ed1\u4eba|l=Black people in Guangzhou|labels=no}}) are [[Emigration from Africa|Africans]] who travel to or reside in [[Guangzhou]], [[People's Republic of China|China]] for short and long term periods.\n\nBeginning during the [[Chinese economic reform|late 1990s economic boom]], an influx of thousands of African traders and business people, predominantly from [[West Africa]], arrived in Guangzhou and created an African community in the middle of the southern Chinese metropolis.<ref name=\"star\">{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Bill|title=Big trouble in China's Chocolate City|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/article/674969|newspaper=Toronto Star|accessdate=2010-05-15|date=2009-08-01}}</ref> At 2012, there was an estimation of more than 100,000 Africans living in Guangzhou.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2016/06/26/asia/africans-leaving-guangzhou-china/ The African migrants giving up on the Chinese dream], CNN, 2016-06-26</ref> Since 2014, the city's African population has significantly declined due to strict immigration enforcement by Chinese authorities and economic pressures in home countries including depreciation of the [[Nigerian naira]] and [[Angolan kwanza]].<ref name=\"tia\">{{cite news|title=Going east: African migrants head for China|url=http://www.thisisafricaonline.com/News/Going-east-African-migrants-head-for-China|newspaper=This is Africa|date=February 2014|access-date=2014-02-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222154143/http://www.thisisafricaonline.com/News/Going-east-African-migrants-head-for-China|archive-date=2014-02-22|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite news|title=The African migrants giving up on the Chinese dream|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/06/26/asia/africans-leaving-guangzhou-china/|agency=CNN|date=September 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"cna\">{{cite news|title=African migrants leaving Guangzhou's Little Africa|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/african-migrants-leaving-guangzhou-s-little-africa/3376408.html|agency=Channel NewsAsia|date=December 19, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"depreciation\">{{cite news |title=Guangzhou to Nigera - Forex Issues |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aRzY-MQMdR4 |work=NTAnews24 |date=September 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Population==\n[[File:African area, Guangzhou - 01.jpg|thumb|300px|The southern end of Baohan Straight Street, [[Dengfeng Subdistrict, Guangzhou|Dengfeng Subdistrict]], Yuexiu District, Guangzhou, Guangdong, China]]\n[[File:African area, Guangzhou - 02.jpg|thumb|300px|Africans in Guangzhou, 2014.]]\n\nMost of these hundreds of thousands of Africans who arrive in Guangzhou are short term visitors making a purchasing run, making population figures liquid and difficult to estimate.<ref name=officials/> According to official figures, 430,000 arrivals and exits by nationals from African countries were recorded at the city's checkpoints in the first nine months of 2014.<ref name=officials/> Guangzhou officials released official population figures for residents in 2014 due to popular fears of an [[Ebola outbreak]] in the city by way of the African community. According to the city, there were 16,000 Africans including North Africans residing in Guangzhou.<ref name=officials>{{cite news|last1=Zhuang|first1=Pinghui|title=Guangzhou clarifies size of African community amid fears over Ebola virus|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1629415/guangzhou-clarifies-size-african-community-amid-fears-over-ebola-virus|date=November 1, 2014}}</ref> Of these residents, 4,000 were long term residents, which is defined by city officials as living for longer than 6 months in the city.<ref name=yen>{{cite news|title=\u5728\u5e7f\u5dde\u5c45\u4f4f\u5916\u56fd\u4eba\u8fbe11.8\u4e07 \u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u6700\u591a\u97e9\u56fd\u5c45\u6b21|url=http://www.ycwb.com/ePaper/xkb/html/2014-12/01/content_592212.htm|newspaper=Yangcheng Evening News|access-date=2015-02-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203093224/http://www.ycwb.com/ePaper/xkb/html/2014-12/01/content_592212.htm|archive-date=2015-02-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSince 2014 the African population has significantly declined, dropping to 10,344 residents by February 2017.<ref name=\"pop2017\"/> A 2014 article in the magazine ''[[This Is Africa]]'' noted the decrease in population with increased immigration enforcement and foreign exchange difficulties blamed.<ref name=\"tia\"/><ref name=\"depreciation\"/> A [[CNN]] article from September 2016 on the community claimed that upwards to thousands of African residents had left the city in the previous 18 months.<ref name=cnn/>\n\nAmong African nationalities in Guangzhou, the two countries with by far the most people are the West African nations of Nigeria and Mali.<ref name=overstay>{{cite news|title=How many Africans are there in Guangzhou|url=http://africansinchina.net/how-many-africans-are-there-in-guangzhou/|date=November 2014}}</ref> Nigerian people, mostly of the [[Igbo people|Igbo]] ethnicity, are most represented among those residing while Malians according to city records are most numerous among long term residents.<ref name=yen/><ref name=overstay/><ref name=\"neighborhoods\">{{cite book|last1=Mathews|first1=Gordon|last2=Dan Lin|first2=Linessa|last3=Yang|first3=Yang|title=The World in Guangzhou|date=2017|publisher=University of Chicago Press|pages=23\u201324}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Migration and business: Weaving the world together |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |date=2011-11-19 |url=http://www.economist.com/node/21538700 |access-date=2014-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Igbos, other Africans making it big in China |publisher=PM News Nigeria |url=http://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2013/09/20/igbos-other-africans-making-it-big-in-china |access-date=2015-04-12|date=2013-09-20 }}</ref>  Migrants from the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]], [[Ghana]], and [[Senegal]] are the remaining African communities in Guangzhou with at least a few hundred registered members at country-based civic organizations in 2014.<ref name=overstay/>\n\n==Neighborhoods==\nThere are two main areas where Africans live and do business in Guangzhou: Xiaobei and Guangyuanxi, both areas in the centrally located [[Yuexiu District]].<ref name=\"neighborhoods\"/>\n\nThe area of Xiaobei is near [[Xiaobei station]] and home to several streets catering to African and Middle Eastern residents. Since the area was home to an existing Muslim population from [[Ningxia]] and [[Xinjiang]], many African immigrants, around half of whom are Muslims, congregated around one area of town primarily because of the convenience in finding [[halal food]].<ref name=net2>{{cite news|title=\u975e\u6d32\u9ed1\u4eba\u5728\u5e7f\u5dde Black People in Guangzhou|author=Zhen Jinghui|url=http://www.nfcmag.com/articles/1648/page/1|accessdate=2011-09-06|newspaper=Nanfengchuang|date=2009-09-11}}</ref> Owing to the neighborhood's history there are slightly more Muslim Africans than Christian Africans in Xiaobei.<ref name=\"neighborhoods\"/> The nerve center of the area is Baohan Straight Street where there are African orientated shops and restaurants.<ref name=\"neighborhoods\"/> The street was repaved in 2015 and many of the hawkers have departed or set up shops.<ref name=\"neighborhoods\"/>\n\nAbout 2 miles from Xiaobei and north of the [[Guangzhou railway station]] is Guangyuanxi, a more business orientated area with a major presence of Nigerian [[Igbo people]].<ref name=\"neighborhoods\"/> The area is filled with large trademarts selling shoes, clothing, and other goods.<ref name=\"neighborhoods\"/> The trademarts are housed in large buildings called Tong Tong Trade Mart, Tian'en Clothing Market, Tangqi Building, Canaan Market, and Ying Fu Building. Since stricter immigration enforcement in the summer of 2013, this area has become much more dormant than before.<ref name=\"neighborhoods\"/>\n\n==History==\n===1990s and 2000s===\nSince China's economic boom in the 1990s, thousands of Africans migrated to China; most of these migrants were from West Africa.<ref name=\"star\"/> In Guangzhou, Africans are generally engaged in commerce, visiting or residing in the city because of its wholesale trading markets supplied by nearby factories.<ref name=officials/> During the 2000s, the city's African population rapidly increased with a 2008 news report stating the number of African residents had increased by 30% to 40% annually.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pan|first=Xiaobo|title=Chocolate City - Africans searching for the Chinese Dream|url=http://www.infzm.com/content/6446/0|newspaper=Southern Weekend|date=2008-01-23}}</ref>\n\n===Riots in 2009 and 2012===\nConflict between the African community and police in Guangzhou resulted in riots in 2009 and 2012. In July 2009, two Nigerian men jumped several floors from a building in an attempt to flee Chinese immigration authorities.<ref name=\"death\">{{cite news|title=Africans protest in Guangzhou after passport checks|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2009-07/16/content_8435559.htm|newspaper=China Daily|date=July 16, 2009}}</ref> Both men were hurt from the fall.<ref name=\"riots\">{{cite news|title=Strike Hard Against Immigration: China's New Exit-Entry Law|url=http://www.refworld.org/docid/52973f244.html|work=China Brief|date=November 22, 2013}}</ref> But on hearing rumors of their deaths, hundreds of Africans, mostly Nigerian, surrounded a local police station.<ref name=\"riots\"/> The demonstration escalated into a riot that shut down eight lanes of traffic on a major thoroughfare for several hours.<ref name=\"death\" /><ref name=\"star2\">{{cite news|title=Africans Protest in Guangzhou (Video)|url=https://www.thestar.com/videozone/674349--africans-protest-in-guangzhou|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=2009-07-30}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, an African held in police custody after a taxi fare dispute died after according to police \"suddenly losing consciousness\".<ref name=\"protest\">{{cite news|title=Protest in China over Guangzhou death in custody|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-18516876|newspaper=BBC News|date=20 June 2012}}</ref> Over a hundred Africans gathered at the police station in question demanding the know the cause of death. Guangzhou police responded with a statement that they would \"investigate and settle this case strictly by law\" and also that \"All should abide by the law of China, no one should harm public interests or damage public order.\"<ref name=\"protest\" />\n\n===Stricter immigration enforcement===\nA large scale immigration enforcement sweep was conducted by local police in July\u2013August 2013.<ref name=\"mathews\">{{cite book|last1=Mathews|first1=Gordon|last2=Lin|first2=Linessa Dan|last3=Yang|first3=Yang|title=The World in Guangzhou|date=2017|publisher=University of Chicago Press|pages=118}}</ref> Media reports have reported a decline in the local African population since 2014 with stricter immigration cited as one of the reasons.<ref name=\"tia\"/><ref name=cnn/>\n\nThe system of immigration that had been in place since 2013 in Yuexiu District appeared to undergo change in summer 2018 with media reports that several low cost hotels and apartments in the area had prohibited African guests or singled out passport holders from [[Uganda]] and [[Nigeria]], and shops and restaurants catering to Africans had been closed.<ref name=\"supchina\">{{cite news |title='Not Allowed To Receive African Guests': Discrimination At Guangzhou Hotels |url=https://supchina.com/2018/08/08/not-allowed-to-receive-african-guests-discrimination-at-guangzhou-hotels/ |work=supchina |date=August 8, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"dailymonitor\">{{cite news |title=China cracks down on Ugandans, Nigerians |url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/China-cracks-down--Ugandans--Nigerians/688334-4686402-9ma6epz/index.html |work=Daily Monitor |date=July 29, 2018}}</ref> The Uganda daily ''[[Daily Monitor]]'' spoke to Ugandans in Guangzhou who reported being advised to stay in more costly 4 or 5 star hotels, and other sources for the newspaper claimed the crackdown targeting Ugandans had followed an increasing number of criminal suspects in China charged with drug trafficking holding Ugandan passports, with the suspects allegedly being Nigerian citizens that obtained Ugandan passports through bribing \"rogue\" Ugandan immigration officials.<ref name=\"dailymonitor\"/> A newspaper source described as a \"senior government official\" in Uganda blamed the [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Uganda)|Ministry of Internal Affairs]] for illegally selling Ugandan passports.<ref name=\"dailymonitor\"/> A spokesperson for the Directorate of Citizenship and Immigration Control, under the Ministry of Internal Affairs, responded that the Uganda passports were stolen or sold by Ugandan individuals.<ref name=\"dailymonitor\"/>\n\n===Covid-19 epidemic===\nOn 4 April 2020, it was reported that a Nigerian patient in Guangzhou, who diagnosed [[Covid-19]], did not cooperate with the treatment, and injured a nurse in the hospital.<ref name=\"injury\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gd.gov.cn/gdywdt/zwzt/fkyq/gdzxd/content/post_2963657.html|title=\u4e00\u5916\u7c4d\u786e\u8bca\u60a3\u8005\u5728\u533b\u9662\u6253\u4f24\u62a4\u58eb\u88ab\u7acb\u5211\u4e8b\u6848\u4ef6|last=|first=|date=2 April 2020|website=gd.gov.cn|publisher=People's Government of Guangdong Province|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nOn 7 April, Guangzhou government notified 5 Nigerians who had a positive result on the coronavirus test. The government also claimed that, because of the risk of cluster infections of the African communities, Guangdong Province has raised the risk of outbreaks into an intermediate level of [[Yuexiu District]] and [[Baiyun District, Guangzhou|Baiyun District]] in Guangzhou City, where the Africans usually inhabit. <ref name=\"storm\">{{Cite news|last=\u8521|first=\u5a2a\u5ae3|url=https://www.storm.mg/article/2510017|title=\u75ab\u60c5\u8b93\u4e2d\u570b\u4eba\u66f4\u6b67\u8996\u9ed1\u4eba\uff1f\u5ee3\u5dde\u5927\u91cf\u975e\u88d4\u4eba\u58eb\u6d41\u843d\u8857\u982d\u3000\u906d\u623f\u6771\u8d95\u51fa\u5bb6\u9580\u3001\u627e\u65c5\u9928\u6295\u5bbf\u4e5f\u78b0\u58c1|date=12 April 2020|work=The Storm Media|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> A large number of Africans had been evicted from flats and hotels by landlords, and they also had difficulty on finding food and shelter. They became homeless and slept on the street.<ref name=\"cnn2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/10/china/africans-guangzhou-china-coronavirus-hnk-intl/index.html|title=Africans in Guangzhou on edge as coronavirus fears spark anti-foreigner sentiment in China|last=CNN|first=Jenni Marsh, Shawn Deng and Nectar Gan|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3079497/us-warns-african-americans-avoid-guangzhou-after-reports-black|title=US warns African-Americans to avoid Guangzhou due to discrimination fears|date=2020-04-11|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, the [[Consulate General of the United States, Guangzhou|US Consulate General Guangzhou]] warned the African-Americans to avoid travel to the Guangzhou city, with a report by some African-Americans that \"some businesses and hotels refuse to do business with them\".<ref name=\"cnn2\"/> The Consulate further raised a travelling warning to announce the discrimination condition against African-Americans in Guangzhou on 13 April. In that warning, it said that Chinese officials might require Africans to participate in the Covid-19 test and undergo a 14-day supervised quarantine at their own expense.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://china.usembassy-china.org.cn/health-alert-u-s-consulate-general-guangzhou-peoples-republic-of-china/|title=Health Alert: U.S. Consulate General Guangzhou, People\u2019s Republic of China|date=2020-04-13|website=U.S. Embassy & Consulates in China|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nAmbassadors in China from many African countries wrote to [[Foreign Minister of the People's Republic of China]], [[Wang Yi (politician)|Wang Yi]], for asking China to resolve the discrimination problem against Africans in Guangzhou.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/ch/component/k2/1520303-20200413.htm?|title=\u5728\u7a57\u975e\u88d4\u4eba\u7591\u906d\u6b67\u8996 \u5916\u4ea4\u90e8\u7a31\u53cd\u5c0d\u7a2e\u65cf\u4e3b\u7fa9 - RTHK|website=news.rthk.hk|language=zh-hk|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The chair of [[African Union Commission]], Moussa Faki Mahamat, also summoned Chinese Ambassador to the [[African Union|AU]], Liu Yuxi, to express his extreme concern.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Press|first=The Associated|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/04/11/world/africa/ap-af-virus-outbreak-africa.html|title=African Nations, US Decry Racism Against Blacks in China|date=2020-04-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n\nOn 12 April, [[Zhao Lijian]], the spokesperson of [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China]], claimed that:<ref name=\"Zhao\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/xwfw_665399/s2510_665401/t1768779.shtml|title=Foreign Ministry Spokesperson Zhao Lijian's Remarks on Guangdong's Anti-epidemic Measures Concerning African Citizens in China|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the People's Republic of China|last=|first=|date=12 April 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n{{Cquote|During our fight against the coronavirus, the Chinese government has been attaching great importance to the life and health of foreign nationals in China. All foreigners are treated equally. We reject differential treatment, and we have zero tolerance for discrimination. Since the outbreak, the authorities in Guangdong attach high importance to the treatment of foreign patients, including African nationals. Specific plans and proper arrangements are made to protect their life and health to the best of our ability, thanks to which we were able to save the lives of some African patients in severe or critical conditions.}}\nHe also claimed in the regular press conference on 13 April that China will attach the \"African friends\u2019 concerns\" by adopting a series of measures to avoid racist and discrimination problems, and condemned \"the US had better focus on domestic efforts to contain the spread of the virus. Attempts to use the pandemic to drive a wedge between China and Africa are bound to fail\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/xwfw_665399/s2510_665401/t1769241.shtml|title=Foreign Ministry Spokesperson Zhao Lijian's Regular Press Conference on April 13, 2020|last=|first=|date=13 April 2020|website=|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the People's Republic of China|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Immigration issues==\nSome Africans have applied for permanent residency or work permits, but they are the minority. Many are traders on [[tourist visa]]s engaged in import-export between China and Africa.<ref name=star/>\n\nMany Africans in Guangzhou have overstayed their visas or are using false [[passport]]s{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}, causing local police to conduct frequent visa inspections. Some Africans say that overstaying in China is inevitable because it is impossible to finish off the business they had come for within a 30-day time frame and they cannot afford a plane ticket home.<ref name=star/> Sociologists Gordon Mathews, Linessa Dan Lin, Yang Yang in a study of the local African community note that Nigerians, particularly [[Igbos]], are much more likely than other African groups to stay illegally due to \"masculine pride\".<ref name=\"mathews\"/> Based on field interviews, Igbos report being under greater pressure from family and peers to become a success to justify a trip to China.<ref name=\"mathews\"/>\n\n==Foreign exchange difficulties==\nIn addition to immigration enforcement, another difficulty to navigate for African traders has been the depreciation of several African currencies after the [[2010s oil glut|fall]] in oil prices since 2014.<ref name=\"ft\">{{cite news |title=Commodity dip hits China's little Africa |url=https://www.ft.com/content/74a878fc-3b68-11e6-93e1-426e2e7bb8ad |work=Financial Times |date=July 4, 2016}}</ref> Nigerian traders who are a large part of the African contingent reported being stymied by the difficulty of obtaining foreign currency in Nigeria needed to purchase goods.<ref name=\"depreciation\"/> The Nigerian government had initially reacted to the sharp depreciation in the [[Nigerian naira]] by limiting access to foreign exchange and refusing to devalue the official [[exchange rate]].<ref name=\"ft\"/> In order to obtain naira, Nigerian traders had to resort to the black market to buy dollars at a 75% premium, making it difficult to turn a profit.<ref name=\"depreciation\"/><ref name=\"ft\"/> The foreign exchange problem proved so discouraging that one long time Nigerian clothing trader in Guangzhou interviewed by the ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported being unable to fill a single container so far into the year in the middle of 2016.<ref name=\"ft\"/> Difficulties were reported by traders with foreign exchange in other African countries including Angola, another top oil producer.<ref name=\"depreciation\"/>\n\n==Crime==\nData from Guangdong anti-drug officials indicate that most drug dealers in the province are from Africa or the Middle East.<ref name=07guangzhou946>{{cite journal|title=07GUANGZHOU946_a|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/07GUANGZHOU946_a.html|publisher=Wikileaks}}</ref><ref name=drugs>{{cite news|last=Wang|first=Huazhong|title=More foreigners involved in drug trafficking cases|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/photo/2010-06/26/content_10023151.htm|newspaper=China Daily|date=2010-06-26}}</ref> Anti-drug officials quoted by US diplomats in a 2007 diplomatic cable described linguistic difficulties faced by the police in countering African drug dealers, noting some dealers used languages like [[Igbo language|Igbo]], a Nigerian language that police had no capability for understanding.<ref name=07guangzhou946/> A Nigerian consulate official in Guangzhou estimated in 2017 that on average 1% of Nigerians arriving in Guangzhou would be arrested for a drug-related offense.<ref name=\"consulate\">{{cite news |title=535 Nigerians languish in Chinese prisons for drug trafficking |url=https://www.thepointng.com/535-nigerians-languish-in-chinese-prisons-for-drug-trafficking/ |work=The Point |date=May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Guangzhou Public Security Bureau carried out a major drug bust with 1,300 police officers raiding the Lihua Hotel (Dragon Hotel) in the city's [[Yuexiu District]]. The August 2013 raid coincided with an immigration enforcement crackdown in the summer 2013 and led to the arrest of 168 suspects, most of whom were described by police as citizens of Nigeria and Mali.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guangzhou police smash West African-led drugs ring|url=http://www.dongguantoday.com/news/guangdong/201308/t20130815_2526371.shtml|newspaper=Dongguan Today|date=2013-08-15}}</ref> The then Nigerian Ambassador in Beijing, Sola Onadipe, stated that more than 50 of the suspects arrested were holders of Nigerian passports. He noted large amounts of money were found on the suspects and lamented in an interview with the [[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard]], \"As an embassy, how do you tackle such a thing?\"<ref name=\"ambassador\">{{cite news|title=Nigerians' notoriety in China is unprecedented - Ambassdaor Onadipe|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2014/02/nigerians-notoriety-china-unprecedented-ambassador-onadipe/|work=The Vanguard|date=February 16, 2014}}</ref> The Ambassador in the same interview, a year before planned retirement, was harsh on his countrymen for engaging in what he described as rampant drug trafficking and ill mannered public behavior (\"smoking [[marijuana]] openly in another man's country\") and vented \"it makes you not to enjoy your job\".<ref name=\"ambassador\"/> Ambassador Onadipe gave the local police credit for fairly adjudicating criminal cases involving Nigerians and pointed out that other African communities in Guangzhou including the neighboring countries of [[Ivory Coast]] and [[Ghana]] and countries across [[Francophone Africa]] didn't get the same level of police attention as Nigerians.<ref name=\"ambassador\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Dengfeng Subdistrict}}\n{{Portal|China|Africa}}\n*[[Hao Ge]]\n*[[Africans in Hong Kong]]\n*[[Racism in the People's Republic of China]]\n*[[Chinese people in Nigeria]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{in lang|fr}} Grangereau, Philippe. \"[http://www.liberation.fr/monde/2013/10/27/chinenoirs-desespoirs_942712 Noirs d\u00e9sespoirs en Chine]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6XYK5Doqa Archive]). ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]''. 27 October 2013.\n\n{{Immigration to China}}\n{{Immigration from Africa}}\n{{Igbo topics}}\n{{Ethnic enclaves}}\n\n[[Category:Africa\u2013China relations]]\n[[Category:African diaspora in China|Guangzhou]]\n[[Category:Chinese people of African descent|*]]\n[[Category:People from Guangzhou]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in China]]\n[[Category:Immigration to China]]\n[[Category:Igbo diaspora|Guangzhou]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group= Africans in Guangzhou\n|population= 10,344 (2017)<ref name=\"pop2017\">{{cite news|title=Guangzhou community shrinks under police pressure, economic changes|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1039623.shtml|agency=[[Global Times]]|date=March 26, 2017}}</ref>\n|popplace= \n|langs= [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], [[Igbo language|Igbo]], [[Bambara language|Bambara]] and other [[Languages of Africa|African languages]]\n|rels= {{hlist| [[Christianity]] | [[Islam]] | [[Traditional African religion|traditional faiths]] }}\n|related= \n}}{{Chinese\n|order=st\n|s=\u5e7f\u5dde\u975e\u88d4\n|t=\u5ee3\u5dde\u975e\u88d4\n|p=Gu\u01cengzh\u014du F\u0113iy\u00ec\n|j=gwong2 zau1 fei1 jeoi6\n|l=Guangzhou residents of African descent\n|s2=\u5e7f\u5dde\u9ed1\u4eba\n|t2=\u5ee3\u5dde\u9ed1\u4eba\n|p2=Gu\u01cengzh\u014du h\u0113ir\u00e9n\n|j2=gwong2 zau1 hak1 jan4\n|l2=Black people in Guangzhou\n}}\n'''Africans in Guangzhou''' ({{zh|s=\u5e7f\u5dde\u975e\u88d4|t=\u5ee3\u5dde\u975e\u88d4}}, more commonly {{zh|s=\u5e7f\u5dde\u9ed1\u4eba|t=\u5ee3\u5dde\u9ed1\u4eba|l=Black people in Guangzhou|labels=no}}) are [[Emigration from Africa|Africans]] who travel to or reside in [[Guangzhou]], [[People's Republic of China|China]] for short and long term periods.\n\nBeginning during the [[Chinese economic reform|late 1990s economic boom]], an influx of thousands of African traders and business people, predominantly from [[West Africa]], arrived in Guangzhou and created an African community in the middle of the southern Chinese metropolis.<ref name=\"star\">{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Bill|title=Big trouble in China's Chocolate City|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/article/674969|newspaper=Toronto Star|accessdate=2010-05-15|date=2009-08-01}}</ref> At 2012, there was an estimation of more than 100,000 Africans living in Guangzhou.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2016/06/26/asia/africans-leaving-guangzhou-china/ The African migrants giving up on the Chinese dream], CNN, 2016-06-26</ref> Since 2014, the city's African population has significantly declined due to strict immigration enforcement by Chinese authorities and economic pressures in home countries including depreciation of the [[Nigerian naira]] and [[Angolan kwanza]].<ref name=\"tia\">{{cite news|title=Going east: African migrants head for China|url=http://www.thisisafricaonline.com/News/Going-east-African-migrants-head-for-China|newspaper=This is Africa|date=February 2014|access-date=2014-02-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222154143/http://www.thisisafricaonline.com/News/Going-east-African-migrants-head-for-China|archive-date=2014-02-22|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite news|title=The African migrants giving up on the Chinese dream|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/06/26/asia/africans-leaving-guangzhou-china/|agency=CNN|date=September 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"cna\">{{cite news|title=African migrants leaving Guangzhou's Little Africa|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/african-migrants-leaving-guangzhou-s-little-africa/3376408.html|agency=Channel NewsAsia|date=December 19, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"depreciation\">{{cite news |title=Guangzhou to Nigera - Forex Issues |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aRzY-MQMdR4 |work=NTAnews24 |date=September 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Population==\n[[File:African area, Guangzhou - 01.jpg|thumb|300px|The southern end of Baohan Straight Street, [[Dengfeng Subdistrict, Guangzhou|Dengfeng Subdistrict]], Yuexiu District, Guangzhou, Guangdong, China]]\n[[File:African area, Guangzhou - 02.jpg|thumb|300px|Africans in Guangzhou, 2014.]]\n\nMost of these hundreds of thousands of Africans who arrive in Guangzhou are short term visitors making a purchasing run, making population figures liquid and difficult to estimate.<ref name=officials/> According to official figures, 430,000 arrivals and exits by nationals from African countries were recorded at the city's checkpoints in the first nine months of 2014.<ref name=officials/> Guangzhou officials released official population figures for residents in 2014 due to popular fears of an [[Ebola outbreak]] in the city by way of the African community. According to the city, there were 16,000 Africans including North Africans residing in Guangzhou.<ref name=officials>{{cite news|last1=Zhuang|first1=Pinghui|title=Guangzhou clarifies size of African community amid fears over Ebola virus|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1629415/guangzhou-clarifies-size-african-community-amid-fears-over-ebola-virus|date=November 1, 2014}}</ref> Of these residents, 4,000 were long term residents, which is defined by city officials as living for longer than 6 months in the city.<ref name=yen>{{cite news|title=\u5728\u5e7f\u5dde\u5c45\u4f4f\u5916\u56fd\u4eba\u8fbe11.8\u4e07 \u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u6700\u591a\u97e9\u56fd\u5c45\u6b21|url=http://www.ycwb.com/ePaper/xkb/html/2014-12/01/content_592212.htm|newspaper=Yangcheng Evening News|access-date=2015-02-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203093224/http://www.ycwb.com/ePaper/xkb/html/2014-12/01/content_592212.htm|archive-date=2015-02-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSince 2014 the African population has significantly declined, dropping to 10,344 residents by February 2017.<ref name=\"pop2017\"/> A 2014 article in the magazine ''[[This Is Africa]]'' noted the decrease in population with increased immigration enforcement and foreign exchange difficulties blamed.<ref name=\"tia\"/><ref name=\"depreciation\"/> A [[CNN]] article from September 2016 on the community claimed that upwards to thousands of African residents had left the city in the previous 18 months.<ref name=cnn/>\n\nAmong African nationalities in Guangzhou, the two countries with by far the most people are the West African nations of Nigeria and Mali.<ref name=overstay>{{cite news|title=How many Africans are there in Guangzhou|url=http://africansinchina.net/how-many-africans-are-there-in-guangzhou/|date=November 2014}}</ref> Nigerian people, mostly of the [[Igbo people|Igbo]] ethnicity, are most represented among those residing while Malians according to city records are most numerous among long term residents.<ref name=yen/><ref name=overstay/><ref name=\"neighborhoods\">{{cite book|last1=Mathews|first1=Gordon|last2=Dan Lin|first2=Linessa|last3=Yang|first3=Yang|title=The World in Guangzhou|date=2017|publisher=University of Chicago Press|pages=23\u201324}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Migration and business: Weaving the world together |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |date=2011-11-19 |url=http://www.economist.com/node/21538700 |access-date=2014-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Igbos, other Africans making it big in China |publisher=PM News Nigeria |url=http://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2013/09/20/igbos-other-africans-making-it-big-in-china |access-date=2015-04-12|date=2013-09-20 }}</ref>  Migrants from the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]], [[Ghana]], and [[Senegal]] are the remaining African communities in Guangzhou with at least a few hundred registered members at country-based civic organizations in 2014.<ref name=overstay/>\n\n==Neighborhoods==\nThere are two main areas where Africans live and do business in Guangzhou: Xiaobei and Guangyuanxi, both areas in the centrally located [[Yuexiu District]].<ref name=\"neighborhoods\"/>\n\nThe area of Xiaobei is near [[Xiaobei station]] and home to several streets catering to African and Middle Eastern residents. Since the area was home to an existing Muslim population from [[Ningxia]] and [[Xinjiang]], many African immigrants, around half of whom are Muslims, congregated around one area of town primarily because of the convenience in finding [[halal food]].<ref name=net2>{{cite news|title=\u975e\u6d32\u9ed1\u4eba\u5728\u5e7f\u5dde Black People in Guangzhou|author=Zhen Jinghui|url=http://www.nfcmag.com/articles/1648/page/1|accessdate=2011-09-06|newspaper=Nanfengchuang|date=2009-09-11}}</ref> Owing to the neighborhood's history there are slightly more Muslim Africans than Christian Africans in Xiaobei.<ref name=\"neighborhoods\"/> The nerve center of the area is Baohan Straight Street where there are African orientated shops and restaurants.<ref name=\"neighborhoods\"/> The street was repaved in 2015 and many of the hawkers have departed or set up shops.<ref name=\"neighborhoods\"/>\n\nAbout 2 miles from Xiaobei and north of the [[Guangzhou railway station]] is Guangyuanxi, a more business orientated area with a major presence of Nigerian [[Igbo people]].<ref name=\"neighborhoods\"/> The area is filled with large trademarts selling shoes, clothing, and other goods.<ref name=\"neighborhoods\"/> The trademarts are housed in large buildings called Tong Tong Trade Mart, Tian'en Clothing Market, Tangqi Building, Canaan Market, and Ying Fu Building. Since stricter immigration enforcement in the summer of 2013, this area has become much more dormant than before.<ref name=\"neighborhoods\"/>\n\n==History==\n===1990s and 2000s===\nSince China's economic boom in the 1990s, thousands of Africans migrated to China; most of these migrants were from West Africa.<ref name=\"star\"/> In Guangzhou, Africans are generally engaged in commerce, visiting or residing in the city because of its wholesale trading markets supplied by nearby factories.<ref name=officials/> During the 2000s, the city's African population rapidly increased with a 2008 news report stating the number of African residents had increased by 30% to 40% annually.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pan|first=Xiaobo|title=Chocolate City - Africans searching for the Chinese Dream|url=http://www.infzm.com/content/6446/0|newspaper=Southern Weekend|date=2008-01-23}}</ref>\n\n===Riots in 2009 and 2012===\nConflict between the African community and police in Guangzhou resulted in riots in 2009 and 2012. In July 2009, two Nigerian men jumped several floors from a building in an attempt to flee Chinese immigration authorities.<ref name=\"death\">{{cite news|title=Africans protest in Guangzhou after passport checks|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2009-07/16/content_8435559.htm|newspaper=China Daily|date=July 16, 2009}}</ref> Both men were hurt from the fall.<ref name=\"riots\">{{cite news|title=Strike Hard Against Immigration: China's New Exit-Entry Law|url=http://www.refworld.org/docid/52973f244.html|work=China Brief|date=November 22, 2013}}</ref> But on hearing rumors of their deaths, hundreds of Africans, mostly Nigerian, surrounded a local police station.<ref name=\"riots\"/> The demonstration escalated into a riot that shut down eight lanes of traffic on a major thoroughfare for several hours.<ref name=\"death\" /><ref name=\"star2\">{{cite news|title=Africans Protest in Guangzhou (Video)|url=https://www.thestar.com/videozone/674349--africans-protest-in-guangzhou|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=2009-07-30}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, an African held in police custody after a taxi fare dispute died after according to police \"suddenly losing consciousness\".<ref name=\"protest\">{{cite news|title=Protest in China over Guangzhou death in custody|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-18516876|newspaper=BBC News|date=20 June 2012}}</ref> Over a hundred Africans gathered at the police station in question demanding the know the cause of death. Guangzhou police responded with a statement that they would \"investigate and settle this case strictly by law\" and also that \"All should abide by the law of China, no one should harm public interests or damage public order.\"<ref name=\"protest\" />\n\n===Stricter immigration enforcement===\nA large scale immigration enforcement sweep was conducted by local police in July\u2013August 2013.<ref name=\"mathews\">{{cite book|last1=Mathews|first1=Gordon|last2=Lin|first2=Linessa Dan|last3=Yang|first3=Yang|title=The World in Guangzhou|date=2017|publisher=University of Chicago Press|pages=118}}</ref> Media reports have reported a decline in the local African population since 2014 with stricter immigration cited as one of the reasons.<ref name=\"tia\"/><ref name=cnn/>\n\nThe system of immigration that had been in place since 2013 in Yuexiu District appeared to undergo change in summer 2018 with media reports that several low cost hotels and apartments in the area had prohibited African guests or singled out passport holders from [[Uganda]] and [[Nigeria]], and shops and restaurants catering to Africans had been closed.<ref name=\"supchina\">{{cite news |title='Not Allowed To Receive African Guests': Discrimination At Guangzhou Hotels |url=https://supchina.com/2018/08/08/not-allowed-to-receive-african-guests-discrimination-at-guangzhou-hotels/ |work=supchina |date=August 8, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"dailymonitor\">{{cite news |title=China cracks down on Ugandans, Nigerians |url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/China-cracks-down--Ugandans--Nigerians/688334-4686402-9ma6epz/index.html |work=Daily Monitor |date=July 29, 2018}}</ref> The Uganda daily ''[[Daily Monitor]]'' spoke to Ugandans in Guangzhou who reported being advised to stay in more costly 4 or 5 star hotels, and other sources for the newspaper claimed the crackdown targeting Ugandans had followed an increasing number of criminal suspects in China charged with drug trafficking holding Ugandan passports, with the suspects allegedly being Nigerian citizens that obtained Ugandan passports through bribing \"rogue\" Ugandan immigration officials.<ref name=\"dailymonitor\"/> A newspaper source described as a \"senior government official\" in Uganda blamed the [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Uganda)|Ministry of Internal Affairs]] for illegally selling Ugandan passports.<ref name=\"dailymonitor\"/> A spokesperson for the Directorate of Citizenship and Immigration Control, under the Ministry of Internal Affairs, responded that the Uganda passports were stolen or sold by Ugandan individuals.<ref name=\"dailymonitor\"/>\n\n===Covid-19 epidemic===\nOn 4 April 2020, it was reported that a Nigerian patient in Guangzhou, who diagnosed [[Covid-19]], did not cooperate with the treatment, and injured a nurse in the hospital.<ref name=\"injury\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gd.gov.cn/gdywdt/zwzt/fkyq/gdzxd/content/post_2963657.html|title=\u4e00\u5916\u7c4d\u786e\u8bca\u60a3\u8005\u5728\u533b\u9662\u6253\u4f24\u62a4\u58eb\u88ab\u7acb\u5211\u4e8b\u6848\u4ef6|last=|first=|date=2 April 2020|website=gd.gov.cn|publisher=People's Government of Guangdong Province|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nOn 7 April, Guangzhou government notified 5 Nigerians who had a positive result on the coronavirus test. The government also claimed that, because of the risk of cluster infections of the African communities, Guangdong Province has raised the risk of outbreaks into an intermediate level of [[Yuexiu District]] and [[Baiyun District, Guangzhou|Baiyun District]] in Guangzhou City, where the Africans usually inhabit. <ref name=\"storm\">{{Cite news|last=\u8521|first=\u5a2a\u5ae3|url=https://www.storm.mg/article/2510017|title=\u75ab\u60c5\u8b93\u4e2d\u570b\u4eba\u66f4\u6b67\u8996\u9ed1\u4eba\uff1f\u5ee3\u5dde\u5927\u91cf\u975e\u88d4\u4eba\u58eb\u6d41\u843d\u8857\u982d\u3000\u906d\u623f\u6771\u8d95\u51fa\u5bb6\u9580\u3001\u627e\u65c5\u9928\u6295\u5bbf\u4e5f\u78b0\u58c1|date=12 April 2020|work=The Storm Media|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> A large number of Africans had been evicted from flats and hotels by landlords, and they also had difficulty on finding food and shelter. They became homeless and slept on the street.<ref name=\"cnn2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/10/china/africans-guangzhou-china-coronavirus-hnk-intl/index.html|title=Africans in Guangzhou on edge as coronavirus fears spark anti-foreigner sentiment in China|last=CNN|first=Jenni Marsh, Shawn Deng and Nectar Gan|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3079497/us-warns-african-americans-avoid-guangzhou-after-reports-black|title=US warns African-Americans to avoid Guangzhou due to discrimination fears|date=2020-04-11|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, the [[Consulate General of the United States, Guangzhou|US Consulate General Guangzhou]] warned the African-Americans to avoid travel to the Guangzhou city, with a report by some African-Americans that \"some businesses and hotels refuse to do business with them\".<ref name=\"cnn2\"/> The Consulate further raised a travelling warning to announce the discrimination condition against African-Americans in Guangzhou on 13 April. In that warning, it said that Chinese officials might require Africans to participate in the Covid-19 test and undergo a 14-day supervised quarantine at their own expense.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://china.usembassy-china.org.cn/health-alert-u-s-consulate-general-guangzhou-peoples-republic-of-china/|title=Health Alert: U.S. Consulate General Guangzhou, People\u2019s Republic of China|date=2020-04-13|website=U.S. Embassy & Consulates in China|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nAmbassadors in China from many African countries wrote to [[Foreign Minister of the People's Republic of China]], [[Wang Yi (politician)|Wang Yi]], for asking China to resolve the discrimination problem against Africans in Guangzhou.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/ch/component/k2/1520303-20200413.htm?|title=\u5728\u7a57\u975e\u88d4\u4eba\u7591\u906d\u6b67\u8996 \u5916\u4ea4\u90e8\u7a31\u53cd\u5c0d\u7a2e\u65cf\u4e3b\u7fa9 - RTHK|website=news.rthk.hk|language=zh-hk|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The chair of [[African Union Commission]], Moussa Faki Mahamat, also summoned Chinese Ambassador to the [[African Union|AU]], Liu Yuxi, to express his extreme concern.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Press|first=The Associated|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/04/11/world/africa/ap-af-virus-outbreak-africa.html|title=African Nations, US Decry Racism Against Blacks in China|date=2020-04-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n\nOn 12 April, [[Zhao Lijian]], the spokesperson of [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China]], claimed that:\n{{Cquote|During our fight against the coronavirus, the Chinese government has been attaching great importance to the life and health of foreign nationals in China. All foreigners are treated equally. We reject differential treatment, and we have zero tolerance for discrimination. Since the outbreak, the authorities in Guangdong attach high importance to the treatment of foreign patients, including African nationals. Specific plans and proper arrangements are made to protect their life and health to the best of our ability, thanks to which we were able to save the lives of some African patients in severe or critical conditions.}}<ref name=\"Zhao\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/xwfw_665399/s2510_665401/t1768779.shtml|title=Foreign Ministry Spokesperson Zhao Lijian's Remarks on Guangdong's Anti-epidemic Measures Concerning African Citizens in China|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the People's Republic of China|last=|first=|date=12 April 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\nHe also claimed in the regular press conference on 13 April that China will attach the \"African friends\u2019 concerns\" by adopting a series of measures to avoid racist and discrimination problems, and condemned \"the US had better focus on domestic efforts to contain the spread of the virus. Attempts to use the pandemic to drive a wedge between China and Africa are bound to fail\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/xwfw_665399/s2510_665401/t1769241.shtml|title=Foreign Ministry Spokesperson Zhao Lijian's Regular Press Conference on April 13, 2020|last=|first=|date=13 April 2020|website=|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the People's Republic of China|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Immigration issues==\nSome Africans have applied for permanent residency or work permits, but they are the minority. Many are traders on [[tourist visa]]s engaged in import-export between China and Africa.<ref name=star/>\n\nMany Africans in Guangzhou have overstayed their visas or are using false [[passport]]s{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}, causing local police to conduct frequent visa inspections. Some Africans say that overstaying in China is inevitable because it is impossible to finish off the business they had come for within a 30-day time frame and they cannot afford a plane ticket home.<ref name=star/> Sociologists Gordon Mathews, Linessa Dan Lin, Yang Yang in a study of the local African community note that Nigerians, particularly [[Igbos]], are much more likely than other African groups to stay illegally due to \"masculine pride\".<ref name=\"mathews\"/> Based on field interviews, Igbos report being under greater pressure from family and peers to become a success to justify a trip to China.<ref name=\"mathews\"/>\n\n==Foreign exchange difficulties==\nIn addition to immigration enforcement, another difficulty to navigate for African traders has been the depreciation of several African currencies after the [[2010s oil glut|fall]] in oil prices since 2014.<ref name=\"ft\">{{cite news |title=Commodity dip hits China's little Africa |url=https://www.ft.com/content/74a878fc-3b68-11e6-93e1-426e2e7bb8ad |work=Financial Times |date=July 4, 2016}}</ref> Nigerian traders who are a large part of the African contingent reported being stymied by the difficulty of obtaining foreign currency in Nigeria needed to purchase goods.<ref name=\"depreciation\"/> The Nigerian government had initially reacted to the sharp depreciation in the [[Nigerian naira]] by limiting access to foreign exchange and refusing to devalue the official [[exchange rate]].<ref name=\"ft\"/> In order to obtain naira, Nigerian traders had to resort to the black market to buy dollars at a 75% premium, making it difficult to turn a profit.<ref name=\"depreciation\"/><ref name=\"ft\"/> The foreign exchange problem proved so discouraging that one long time Nigerian clothing trader in Guangzhou interviewed by the ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported being unable to fill a single container so far into the year in the middle of 2016.<ref name=\"ft\"/> Difficulties were reported by traders with foreign exchange in other African countries including Angola, another top oil producer.<ref name=\"depreciation\"/>\n\n==Crime==\nData from Guangdong anti-drug officials indicate that most drug dealers in the province are from Africa or the Middle East.<ref name=07guangzhou946>{{cite journal|title=07GUANGZHOU946_a|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/07GUANGZHOU946_a.html|publisher=Wikileaks}}</ref><ref name=drugs>{{cite news|last=Wang|first=Huazhong|title=More foreigners involved in drug trafficking cases|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/photo/2010-06/26/content_10023151.htm|newspaper=China Daily|date=2010-06-26}}</ref> Anti-drug officials quoted by US diplomats in a 2007 diplomatic cable described linguistic difficulties faced by the police in countering African drug dealers, noting some dealers used languages like [[Igbo language|Igbo]], a Nigerian language that police had no capability for understanding.<ref name=07guangzhou946/> A Nigerian consulate official in Guangzhou estimated in 2017 that on average 1% of Nigerians arriving in Guangzhou would be arrested for a drug-related offense.<ref name=\"consulate\">{{cite news |title=535 Nigerians languish in Chinese prisons for drug trafficking |url=https://www.thepointng.com/535-nigerians-languish-in-chinese-prisons-for-drug-trafficking/ |work=The Point |date=May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Guangzhou Public Security Bureau carried out a major drug bust with 1,300 police officers raiding the Lihua Hotel (Dragon Hotel) in the city's [[Yuexiu District]]. The August 2013 raid coincided with an immigration enforcement crackdown in the summer 2013 and led to the arrest of 168 suspects, most of whom were described by police as citizens of Nigeria and Mali.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guangzhou police smash West African-led drugs ring|url=http://www.dongguantoday.com/news/guangdong/201308/t20130815_2526371.shtml|newspaper=Dongguan Today|date=2013-08-15}}</ref> The then Nigerian Ambassador in Beijing, Sola Onadipe, stated that more than 50 of the suspects arrested were holders of Nigerian passports. He noted large amounts of money were found on the suspects and lamented in an interview with the [[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard]], \"As an embassy, how do you tackle such a thing?\"<ref name=\"ambassador\">{{cite news|title=Nigerians' notoriety in China is unprecedented - Ambassdaor Onadipe|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2014/02/nigerians-notoriety-china-unprecedented-ambassador-onadipe/|work=The Vanguard|date=February 16, 2014}}</ref> The Ambassador in the same interview, a year before planned retirement, was harsh on his countrymen for engaging in what he described as rampant drug trafficking and ill mannered public behavior (\"smoking [[marijuana]] openly in another man's country\") and vented \"it makes you not to enjoy your job\".<ref name=\"ambassador\"/> Ambassador Onadipe gave the local police credit for fairly adjudicating criminal cases involving Nigerians and pointed out that other African communities in Guangzhou including the neighboring countries of [[Ivory Coast]] and [[Ghana]] and countries across [[Francophone Africa]] didn't get the same level of police attention as Nigerians.<ref name=\"ambassador\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Dengfeng Subdistrict}}\n{{Portal|China|Africa}}\n*[[Hao Ge]]\n*[[Africans in Hong Kong]]\n*[[Racism in the People's Republic of China]]\n*[[Chinese people in Nigeria]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{in lang|fr}} Grangereau, Philippe. \"[http://www.liberation.fr/monde/2013/10/27/chinenoirs-desespoirs_942712 Noirs d\u00e9sespoirs en Chine]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6XYK5Doqa Archive]). ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]''. 27 October 2013.\n\n{{Immigration to China}}\n{{Immigration from Africa}}\n{{Igbo topics}}\n{{Ethnic enclaves}}\n\n[[Category:Africa\u2013China relations]]\n[[Category:African diaspora in China|Guangzhou]]\n[[Category:Chinese people of African descent|*]]\n[[Category:People from Guangzhou]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in China]]\n[[Category:Immigration to China]]\n[[Category:Igbo diaspora|Guangzhou]]\n", "name_user": "\u3060\uff0a\u305c", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCovid-19 epidemic:// Edit via Wikiplus", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Africans_in_Guangzhou"}
